I thought I responded to your previous question last week, but I don't see the comment.

I don't think the chance of a false positive is very high - having "UnknownTransactionException" in the string as part of a table name seems improbable.  But the important thing is IF it did occur, the worst thing would be we wouldn't retry for the current Exception that was caught.  In either case, an Exception did occur.

I don't think there is additional work for the pull request
Kind of confused.  Do we need this PR and  PR #440?
Thanks for the suggestion Selva!  I'll resumit
close this PR, further change will be PR #440

I wonder if the following solution might be cleaner. Introduce a new built-in function NULLIFERROR('value_expression') similar to NULLIFZERO('value_expression'). Implicitly add this function for HdfsScan if the CQD HIVE_SCAN_SPECIAL_MODE is set to 2.

To ensure that this change works as expected, can you please add more tests.with CQD set to 2
a) insert into traf_table ...select \* from hive table 
b) consider having some columns have not nullable with the hive columns returning an error
c) consider having all possible data types so that conversion errors are handled as expected

Yes, Selva, I will add more tests. b) should already covered by current test. for c), I do need a list of supported HIVE data types to test fully. I now test with (float, string, int, largeint, smallint). TinyInt failed, but I don't think Trafodion can support tinyint maybe. I will raise this question in the more proper place: mail list maybe.
I agree that NULLIFERROR will be a very clean and good solution, but that requires more knowledge of compiler, that will be a rather big project for me. So I suggest we can go with this not-optimal solution first, and implement the NULLIFERROR as phase II and clean up these code. In the field, we do need this feature. This is a prototype you can call it :-) 
I will add tests asap, and then start to study how to write a new built-in function in Trafodion.

Hi, Selva,
I didn't go with the NULLIFERROR approach at first place because I feel some difficulty and confusing about it, it doesn't looks possible for me instinctively. 
Now, I try to really spend time on this approach, that confusion become more concrete: As far as I understand, a function must have scalar value as operand. In this case, we cannot know the converting result until try to do the real converting first. So how to design the input operand for NULLIFERROR? I cannot figure out how CAST's return value can be used as 'ERROR' and as input to next NULLIFERROR clause.
For example: we can generate such an expression:
   NULLIFERROR( CAST () )
If translate into pCode, it will generate two blocks of pCode instructions, first is for CAST, during pCode execution of that block, if it meets converting error, it will return error to the caller immediately and no chance to go to next block of NULLIFERROR. If we modify the CAST pCode to continue and save error conditions somewhere so next NULLIFERROR can get as input, it will have unknown side effort. And it will be difficult to figure out 'what value is ERROR value?' returned by the CAST function. That will be input to NULLIFERROR. We have nullIndicator in a row, but no errorIndicator. So I am confused here. 
So it needs a lot more details about how to use NULLIFERROR.

Looks good to me. All my other comments are minor concerns.
Thanks for the changes. Looks like there might be a buffer overrun risk in one place. Everything else looks fine.
Looks good to me. Though now there are conflicts to be resolved.
Looks good. However, there are surrounding codes where instanceof could have been used instead of checking the string contains the classname.
I've verified this fix against 2.1 version on master branch. (This was the problem version that prompted this change.)

Can you give me an example of the code you're referring to?  I think I used instance of whenever an Exception was caught.  In other cases where a String was returned I used contains.  I think that is the correct behavior since using instance of would require me to create a new Exception from that String and then attempt to determine if it's an instance of or not.  This doesn't seem appropriate to me, but perhaps this is what you're looking for?
My bad. I misunderstood getException returns Exception object. Change is good to go

Thanks for reviewing guys
